<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/27092793-mel-foster"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1401757419i/27092793._UX100_CR0,4,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/27092793-mel-foster">Mel Foster</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Because Goodreads is wonky, this question comes up for multiple editions. Aesop&apos;s Fables don&apos;t exactly have a clear literary line. If your collection <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Because Goodreads is wonky, this question comes up for multiple editions. Aesop's Fables don't exactly have a clear literary line. If your collection has less than 700+ fables, then it is not all of them. I saw this question because I read the Joseph Jacobs edition. There are many popular editions with many more tales.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
