  <span id="freeText190532128510676802" style="display:none">My colleague S, with whom I'm currently doing a project involving Italian, lent me this book so that I could improve my shaky grasp of her language. I was pleased to find that I could understand quite a lot of it! The high point was discovering an Aesop's Fable that I hadn't previously come across:<br /><br /><b>The Frogs and the Well</b><br /><br />Some frogs lived happily in a puddle. Then summer arrived; as one hot day succeeded another, the puddle shrank until it disappeared altogether. The frogs had no choice but to seek a new home. They hopped painfully along, but everywhere they went they found dried-up ponds and empty river beds. Finally they came to a well. Looking down the deep shaft, they saw water at the bottom. <br /><br />"We're saved!" croaked one frog. "Let's jump in now!"<br /><br />"Wait a moment," said his less impulsive friend. "What will we do if this one also dries up?"<br /></span>
